FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, BOVINE - KAZAKHSTAN (03)
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Tue 5 Jun 2007
Source: Itar-Tass News Agency [edited]
<http://www.itar-tass.com:80/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11596722&PageNum=0>

An outbreak of foot and mouth disease [FMD] has been registered in the
Western Kazakhstan region bordering Russia, the Kazakh Emergencies
Ministry's press service said on Tuesday [5 Jun 2007], and added, "The
quarantine regime has been imposed in the village of Lubyanka,
Chingirlausky district in Western Kazakhstan."
According to the Emergencies Ministry, 160 livestock have been isolated in
the village and 7 veterinary teams have vaccinated another 7000.
The Kazakh Agriculture Ministry reported that 18 000 livestock were
vaccinated on Monday [4 Jun 2007], and that the ministry had imposed a ban
on import and export of cattle and animal products.
According to earlier reports, 138 livestock in Lubyanka had an infection of
unknown etiology.
--
communicated by:
FMD News
FMD Surveillance and Modeling Laboratory
University of California at Davis
<http://fmd.ucdavis.edu>
<fmdnews@ucdavis.edu>
[Earlier this year, in April and May 2007, 2 foci of FMD were reported from
2 distant locations in Kazakhstan; the 1st one, in Karaganda, was
officially submitted to the OIE (Office International des Epizooties; World
Organization for Animal Health) on 24 Apr 2007; the serotype was not
identified. See the report, including a map, at
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=5290>
and read Mod.PC's background commentary in ProMED-mail 20070522.1637.
The 2nd outbreak was reported from the Atyrau region; see map at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/commonwealth/kazakhstan_pol01.jpg>.
Official confirmation, including data on the species involved and the
serotype of the FMD virus involved, relating to the current outbreak as
well as to the previous reported outbreak in Atyrau region, are
anticipated. - Mod.AS]
See Also
